Example: Queuing Theory in a Bayesian Framework

Letâ€™s revisit the same grocery store.

Suppose you already have prior experience suggesting that, historically, around 5 customers per minute tend to arrive.
Thatâ€™s your prior distribution for Î».

Now, after collecting new data, you find that during this month, the rate appears to be slightly lower â€” around 4 customers per minute.

The Bayesian process is:

Start with a prior: Î» ~ belief centered at 5.

Collect data: observe sample data indicating 4 per minute.

Update: apply Bayesâ€™ theorem to get a posterior distribution â€” your updated belief about Î», now centered closer to 4.3.

Over time, as you collect more data:

The posterior distribution becomes narrower, indicating higher confidence.

The influence of the prior diminishes â€” data dominates.

This is one of Bayesian statisticsâ€™ key strengths:

You can incorporate expert knowledge and keep updating your beliefs as real data arrives.

4. Comparing Frequentist vs Bayesian Thinking
Aspect	Frequentist	Bayesian
Philosophy	Probability = long-run frequency	Probability = degree of belief
Parameter treatment	Fixed but unknown constant	Random variable with a probability distribution
Role of prior knowledge	Ignored â€” only data matters	Incorporated through prior distributions
Uncertainty expression	Confidence intervals (based on resampling)	Posterior distributions (belief updates)
Computation	Typically analytical, faster	Often uses computational methods (e.g., MCMC)
Interpretation	â€œWe are 95% confident this interval contains the true parameter.â€	â€œThereâ€™s a 95% probability the parameter lies within this interval.â€
When useful	Large datasets, frequent experiments	Small datasets, domain expertise, or sequential updates
