6. Interpretation Difference Simplified
Question	Frequentist Answer	Bayesian Answer
What is Î» (average arrivals per minute)?	A fixed value estimated from repeated samples.	A probability distribution expressing belief in possible Î» values.
What is uncertainty?	Sampling variability.	Uncertainty in our belief about the parameter.
How to improve certainty?	Collect more data.	Collect more data or refine priors with expert knowledge.
7. Key Takeaways

Frequentist inference depends only on the data â€” it assumes no prior knowledge and focuses on repeatable, long-run frequencies.

Bayesian inference allows for prior beliefs to guide early estimates, updating them as new data comes in.

In real-world business settings (like queuing, forecasting, or customer behavior modeling), Bayesian methods shine when you have limited data but domain expertise â€” while Frequentist methods are efficient when large amounts of data are available.

Both approaches use similar mathematics but differ fundamentally in interpretation and philosophy.
